I'd like to offer a special
thank you to ABAA and especially

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:54.900
to Susan Benny who has carried
the administrative burden

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:58.550
for this contest and has
kept everyone in line

00:07:58.550 --> 00:08:01.800
and has had many wonderful
ideas that we do our best

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:03.870
to incorporate, don't we Susan?

00:08:03.870 --> 00:08:07.070
And we talk about other
ideas and it's interesting

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:09.700
that with the Grolier Club
of course there's a concern

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:13.740
about young collectors, with our
organizations there's a concern

00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:17.920
about young collectors and this
is an alliance I think that all

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:20.970
of us involved in
are working on.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:22.930
The other partner
within the Library

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:26.300
of Congress is the Rare Book
and Special Collections Division

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:30.250
and at this time I'd like to
introduce Mark Dimunation.

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:34.610
Mark is the judge on the part
of the Library of Congress,

00:08:34.610 --> 00:08:36.350
but Mark is more than that.

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:40.630
Mark also is part of the
package that winners get

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:45.340
when they arrive here and
get a program this afternoon,

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:46.640
it was held at the Rare Book

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:50.510
and Special Collections Division
having Mark talk about a few

00:08:50.510 --> 00:08:53.850
of the treasures, we have a
few books and things based

00:08:53.850 --> 00:08:56.550
on collecting and
Mark does that so well

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:58.900
and I know everyone
there appreciates it.

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:02.440
I'd ask Mark to say a word
or two before we move ahead

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:08.860
with our speaker about the
process of judging and come

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:10.540
on Mark you can cover it
up pretty well, come on.

00:09:10.540 --> 00:09:13.510
Let's give Mark a hand.

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:20.810
[ Applause ]

00:09:20.810 --> 00:09:22.110
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: Thank you.

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:23.410
imagine the terrified
look on their faces

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:25.290
when they're informed
I'm part of the package.

00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:29.920
Welcome everybody, it's a
lovely event and for those of us

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:32.960
in the rare book in the
world this is always exciting

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:36.430
because we know we're looking
at the future of collections

00:09:36.430 --> 00:09:40.810
across America, whether they
land in Goucher or the Library

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:42.470
of Congress so that
we're still talking.

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:47.100
I want to give you a sense of
what it's like to participate

00:09:47.100 --> 00:09:50.340
on the end of actually
reading a variety of essays

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:52.060
from young collectors
who are talking

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:55.150
about the reasons
behind why they collect,

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:58.520
how they collected, what
prompted them to begin.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:01.330
For those of us who live
with rare book collections

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:03.030
of course this is
the story we tell

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:05.020
of almost everything we
have in the division,

00:10:05.020 --> 00:10:07.900
so it's a very familiar
tale to be told.

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:10.080
But I just want to give you a
sense of what we were coping

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:15.860
with just in the spirit of
the four prizewinners today.

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:18.260
Imagine if you will
in the reading of more

00:10:18.260 --> 00:10:21.360
than a dozen essays that
include lists of books.

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:22.750
These are the people
who have filtered

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:25.530
through their local
competitions, that have come

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:28.610
to a national competition,
that have then been sifted

00:10:28.610 --> 00:10:30.380
through to a final
round and that's

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:32.380
when the final judges
step in to read.

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:36.140
There are other people in the
room here who are participating

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:39.020
in this conversation
and they can back me up.

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:41.830
It's kind of a wild ride
that we go on in part

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:44.600
because we're confronting
in some cases materials

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:46.680
that we're very familiar
with and we want

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:48.470
to see the particular
take of the collector.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:50.880
In other cases, as is the case

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:53.610
with the first-place
prizewinner, we were introduced

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:55.380
to someone we've never heard of.

00:10:55.380 --> 00:10:58.350
And so, we're introduced
to not only the topic

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:00.270
but also the notion
of collecting

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:01.810
for the first time afresh.

00:11:01.810 --> 00:11:03.240
So, in the range

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:05.800
of the conversations
imagine making a decision

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:09.280
between the collection of a
particular individual who comes

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.980
from Mobile along the southern
coast compared to a collection

00:11:12.980 --> 00:11:16.250
on Sacco and Vanzetti and
finally, to the stories

00:11:16.250 --> 00:11:19.310
of resistance during Jewish
resistance during the Holocaust,

00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:23.360
and then finally a collection
of sailboats from somebody

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:25.100
who lives in New Mexico.

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.430
And to try and wrap your head

00:11:27.430 --> 00:11:31.280
around these what it means is
diving deep into these essays,

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:34.860
which are extremely important to
the understanding and I think,

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:38.180
I suspect may actually be
helpful to the young collectors

00:11:38.180 --> 00:11:40.140
as they're being
asked to explain maybe

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:45.900
for the first time what started
them and why they collect now.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:54.580
So, Megan who collected the
Sacco and Vanzetti books talks

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:57.090
about her first introduction
to the trial and then sort

00:11:57.090 --> 00:12:00.100
of running into conflicting
information and the bother

00:12:00.100 --> 00:12:02.230
that that creates for her
and the effort to sort

00:12:02.230 --> 00:12:04.060
of set the story right.

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:05.470
Whereas, Micaela who's writing

00:12:05.470 --> 00:12:08.400
about Jewish resistance
during the Holocaust,

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:11.880
discovering that there's a great
deal of material from the period

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:14.560
but not so much about
resistance and the need

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:16.590
to keep that story alive.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:19.890
Until we get to Luke's
story about Eugene Walter,

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:22.650
king of the monkeys which I
have to confess I kind of moaned

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:27.720
when I read the title I thought
he's collecting a naturalist.

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:31.930
Well, it couldn't be
further from the truth.

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:35.220
Eugene Walter is an
amazing individual

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:36.520
and we had quite a ride

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:39.980
and ultimately Luke's collection
landed in first place,

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:43.960
not just because of the
nature of Mr. Walter himself

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:47.840
who affiliated himself from
anything from Peggy Guggenheim

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:50.860
to the film Innovate and a Half
to writing cookbooks to talking

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:58.290
about Alabama to going back and
forth to writing about his life,

00:12:58.290 --> 00:13:00.670
one book of which is
called the Untidy Pilgrim.

00:13:00.670 --> 00:13:03.520
It's an amazing ride
of an individual

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:05.050
and you'll hear more
about that later.

00:13:05.050 --> 00:13:09.110
So, it's a difficult
decision to be made,

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:10.850
this is how we make
that judgment.

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:15.300
How true to the topic and
to the goal and the mission

00:13:15.300 --> 00:13:17.650
of their collecting are
these collectors and that's

00:13:17.650 --> 00:13:20.910
when the prizewinners very
quickly sort themselves

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:23.780
out from the other contributors,
all of whom are writing

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:25.500
about interesting collections.

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.570
But what we find in the four

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:31.360
that have been given awards
today is a real passion not just

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:33.750
for the subject, but
also for collecting.

00:13:33.750 --> 00:13:36.260
And it's the combination of
the two, of adding some sort

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:39.350
of material reality to
the interest of the topic

00:13:39.350 --> 00:13:41.960
that they're writing about
that makes them true collectors

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:43.500
in the minds of those
of us who live

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:45.040
with these on a daily basis.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:48.050
These are very erudite
essays in many cases

00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:51.340
and I can say this an old
man now, it makes one proud

00:13:51.340 --> 00:13:55.550
of the next generation who
are writing in full sentences

00:13:55.550 --> 00:14:00.430
about books and that
just warms my heart.

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:04.060
It was lovely to have three
of the four here today to talk

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:07.750
about slightly more
polished collectors in a way,

00:14:07.750 --> 00:14:12.100
giving them a sense of the
family that they've joined

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:15.490
as collectors and the
continuity in the world of books

00:14:15.490 --> 00:14:18.660
of people seeking out books
because they love them

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:21.350
as things, because they
love them as ideas,

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:23.440
because they love them as
something that's come to us

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:27.130
from another person and the
stories that they reveal.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:30.340
So, imagine for a moment,
sitting on the phone

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:33.230
with several individuals
staking your claim

00:14:33.230 --> 00:14:36.440
around a particular topic
and you have a sense

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:38.800
of what it must be like to be
a judge in this competition.

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:40.600
So, congratulations
to everybody.

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:46.500
[ Applause ]

