00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:40.090
of black cooks at work taken
from Toni's gallery of authors

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:41.950
which she will tell us about.

00:17:41.950 --> 00:17:45.050
In 1991, she was the first
African-American woman

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:47.190
to hold the position
of food editor

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:49.210
at a major daily
American newspaper,

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:51.010
the Cleveland Plain Dealer.

00:17:51.010 --> 00:17:54.830
She's been a guest instructor
at Whole Foods Culinary Center

00:17:54.830 --> 00:17:57.640
and appeared on cooking
channels, Foodography

00:17:57.640 --> 00:18:01.930
and the PBS feature Juneteenth
There it is Again Jamboree.

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:05.250
Toni, I'm exhausted, help
get me out of this jam.

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:08.510
Here is Toni Tipton-Martin.

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:14.480
[ Applause ]

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:20.560
&gt;&gt; Toni Tipton-Martin: Thank
you so much, thank you.

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:25.490
Hi. So ordinarily speakers you
know we begin with what an honor

00:18:25.490 --> 00:18:28.210
and a privilege it is
to be here but really,

00:18:28.210 --> 00:18:31.930
I have to say I am a
little silly giddy,

00:18:31.930 --> 00:18:33.920
I'm so excited to be here.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:37.920
This is the place where
my work in some ways began

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:44.920
and so the ability to read the
winning essays as a journalist

00:18:44.920 --> 00:18:48.920
and a reporter, as
an amateur collector

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:54.790
and to read your passion
and to see some of myself

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:58.110
in your writing it
makes me emotional,

00:18:58.110 --> 00:18:59.910
it was just really a privilege

00:18:59.910 --> 00:19:01.210
and it is a privilege
to be here.

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:06.830
So, thank you so
much for having me.

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:10.610
I've passed around a copy of the
card, not because I'm so vain

00:19:10.610 --> 00:19:13.000
that I want you to see the
back with all of the awards,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.590
my publisher did that.

00:19:14.590 --> 00:19:19.110
But I'd like to begin really
the way that I begin everywhere.

00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:21.570
This is the first opportunity
that I've had to speak

00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:24.040
in a new family, a
family of collectors,

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:29.700
a family that is making me
feel a bit of confidence

00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:31.860
about what I've just
experienced.

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:36.080
I speak to so many groups,
food people primarily,

00:19:36.080 --> 00:19:38.780
but I will be speaking at
Duke for example next week

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:41.560
and so there are always people
that have a different kind

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:44.950
of an interest in my
material than people

00:19:44.950 --> 00:19:50.390
who are not necessarily focused
on African-American history

00:19:50.390 --> 00:19:53.570
or Foodways studies,
but as collectors.

00:19:53.570 --> 00:19:57.570
And so, what I've given is
the card that I'm traveling

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:59.520
around with and I ask everybody

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:02.070
to take a minute to
look at the cover.

00:20:02.070 --> 00:20:04.370
This is the cover of the book.

00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:10.620
This is the book, but it doesn't
have the dust jacket on it.

00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:15.770
So, this is the dust jacket that
would be there, how about that?

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:20.490
Take a peek and now
just for a moment notice

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:22.930
that you're having a
reaction to the cover.

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:26.640
It's a little easier when it's
a slide or when it's bigger,

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:30.060
but each of us individually
is having a reaction

00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:31.640
to this picture.

00:20:31.640 --> 00:20:37.460
Whether you recognize
the image as a woman

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:42.500
who might've been a caretaker in
your community, in your family.

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:45.270
There might be a sense
of pride connected

00:20:45.270 --> 00:20:49.090
to memories associated
with this woman.

00:20:49.090 --> 00:20:52.460
There might even be a sense
of shame for some people

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:55.810
that I speak to regarding
this image.

00:20:55.810 --> 00:20:58.730
Whether that is
African-Americans

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:02.390
or white people we
all have a reaction.

00:21:02.390 --> 00:21:05.670
And there's even a
reaction by young people

00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:09.110
who don't have any idea who
she is and what I'm talking

00:21:09.110 --> 00:21:13.030
about because you see packages
with faces on them all the time.

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:16.440
But the reason I ask
everyone to take a moment is

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:21.580
that in our daily busy lives we
go through life having reactions

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:25.800
to things and we're not
always aware of them.

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:29.040
We're being spoken to a lot
now about mindfulness right,

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:32.280
everybody's talking about being
mindful and paying attention.

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:36.980
And so, my work centers
on using food as a tool

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:42.200
for racial reconciliation,
that's my primary purpose.

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:44.020
It's why I won the Egerton prize

00:21:44.020 --> 00:21:49.320
and other great things
that have happened.

00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:57.510
And prejudice occurs one
affront at a time and so my goal

00:21:57.510 --> 00:22:00.120
with writing the
Jemima Code was the hope

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:03.950
that we could restore an
image that has been used

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:08.750
in multiple ways to
distract us, to divide us,

00:22:08.750 --> 00:22:14.870
to degrade one population
and use that image in a way

00:22:14.870 --> 00:22:17.070
that by the time
you get to the end

00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:20.100
of my work we're all
in the same place.

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:22.870
So even though we might start
somewhere differently we will

00:22:22.870 --> 00:22:24.940
all wind up in the same place.

00:22:24.940 --> 00:22:29.710
So, I won't even ask how many of
you have seen the Jemima Code.

00:22:29.710 --> 00:22:34.090
But the Jemima Code
is a bibliography,

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:37.140
an annotated bibliography
and it is the story

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:40.860
of my rare black
book collection.

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:44.740
I'm an amateur accidental
collector,

00:22:44.740 --> 00:22:51.830
I collected these books
as a reporter on a story.

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:55.780
My goal in writing this
book as I've said was

00:22:55.780 --> 00:23:00.540
to describe each one of
these authors in a unique

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:05.390
and unbiased way so that by
the time we get to the end

00:23:05.390 --> 00:23:08.920
of the book we're all
in the same place.

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:11.920
If you can't see it in the back,
there's a little black girl

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:13.220
and a little white girl

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:15.710
and they're going
off into the sunset.

00:23:15.710 --> 00:23:21.330
And this is an image taken from
one of the books from 1978.

00:23:21.330 --> 00:23:24.350
Two authors got together, a
white woman and a black woman

00:23:24.350 --> 00:23:27.230
in Louisiana and
they published a book

00:23:27.230 --> 00:23:29.440
with the same motive
that I have.

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:31.890
I just love that.

00:23:31.890 --> 00:23:36.800
So, I'm going to save one of
these pages because when I look

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:40.940
for it when speaking
I always lose it.

00:23:40.940 --> 00:23:46.070
So, as I said, I
was a journalist

00:23:46.070 --> 00:23:48.070
in pursuit of a story.

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:50.080
I was the nutrition writer

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:55.010
for the Los Angeles Times many
years ago, some 30 years ago

00:23:55.010 --> 00:24:00.530
and I was busy organizing
the cookbooks and working

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:04.010
with the recipes in the
collections, in the archives

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:06.130
in the department and I noticed

00:24:06.130 --> 00:24:07.770
that there were no
African-American

00:24:07.770 --> 00:24:09.380
cookbooks there.

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:11.630
But not only did I notice
there were no cookbooks there I

00:24:11.630 --> 00:24:14.620
noticed that those references

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:18.680
to African-Americans were
usually very disparaging.

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:22.570
They made reference to
this Aunt Jemima character,

00:24:22.570 --> 00:24:28.840
a mythological figure that has
lingered in American history,

00:24:28.840 --> 00:24:32.000
southern history, in
literature, in film.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.380
You will recognize her as the
nanny figure in many of the --

00:24:38.380 --> 00:24:41.360
in everywhere right
in Southern history.

00:24:41.360 --> 00:24:45.340
And I was looking for my
grandmother on the pages

00:24:45.340 --> 00:24:48.560
of Southern history and I
wasn't able to find her there

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:53.220
and certainly not in the way
that I would recognize her.

00:24:53.220 --> 00:24:55.760
And so, I had this idea

00:24:55.760 --> 00:25:00.780
that I would interview
elderly African-American women

00:25:00.780 --> 00:25:03.730
about their true-life
experiences

00:25:03.730 --> 00:25:07.470
and hopefully be able to share
with the rest of the world,

00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:12.130
the passion and the intelligence
and the knowledge and the wisdom

00:25:12.130 --> 00:25:15.860
that I experienced in my own
community through these women.

00:25:15.860 --> 00:25:17.950
And I told a couple of
people that I had that idea

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:19.770
and other books came out.

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:23.110
I'm not from the South I'm from
Los Angeles, so I told people

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:25.090
for example that I was
going to do this book

00:25:25.090 --> 00:25:27.760
by traveling the South and
going to black churches

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:29.860
and that's how I would
find these women.

00:25:29.860 --> 00:25:33.950
And lo and behold somebody came
out with a book on black recipes

00:25:33.950 --> 00:25:36.310
from black churches
in the South.

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:39.400
So, I learned to keep my
idea about my next book very,

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:41.540
very close to the best.

00:25:41.540 --> 00:25:44.650
As a matter fact, so many of
my friends who are scholars

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:48.050
who once this book finally came
out I received so many e-mails

00:25:48.050 --> 00:25:51.410
from people saying we had
no idea what you were doing.

00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:53.750
They knew I was working on
something, but not something

00:25:53.750 --> 00:25:56.710
at this level of beauty.

00:25:56.710 --> 00:25:59.600
So anyway, I was
there at the Times

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:02.360
and I thought I would
interview all these women

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:04.620
and then I realized I didn't
have really any access

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:06.560
to women in the South.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:13.660
And one day there was a little
book, it's the one on the bottom

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:17.470
if you can see in the back, it's
called the New Orleans Cookbook

00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:21.130
by Lena Richard, it
was published in 1985

00:26:21.130 --> 00:26:24.610
and this is a paperback
edition of this book.

00:26:24.610 --> 00:26:27.570
It appeared in a book
giveaway, at the Times

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:30.250
as reporters we weren't allowed
to take anything for free

00:26:30.250 --> 00:26:33.860
and so we would give away books
that came in as review copies

00:26:33.860 --> 00:26:37.320
so that others could
share in those readings.

00:26:37.320 --> 00:26:38.620
And so, this book,

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:41.760
Lena Richard's book
showed up in this pile.

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:43.970
And so, I didn't quite know
what I was going to do with it,

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:45.900
there was no photograph
of the woman in there,

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:47.370
but it was called New Orleans

00:26:47.370 --> 00:26:51.510
and even though I know Southern
food and Creole food are very,

00:26:51.510 --> 00:26:55.290
very different I thought well
it might help me in some way.

00:26:55.290 --> 00:26:58.390
So, I took this book home, I
put it on my shelf with all

00:26:58.390 --> 00:27:03.160
of my other cookbooks and it
sat there for quite a number

00:27:03.160 --> 00:27:05.740
of years, probably
about 10 years.

00:27:05.740 --> 00:27:09.680
And then I was attending
an event in Atlanta

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:15.420
and John Egerton whose name,
in whose name the award

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:19.430
that I received was given was
a Southern sage civil rights

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:25.750
writer, a very important man
in the writings of the South.

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:31.660
And he had just returned from a
visit to the Library of Congress

00:27:31.660 --> 00:27:34.220
and I heard him speak
and he spoke eloquently

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:36.290
about the women in my community.

00:27:36.290 --> 00:27:39.070
He spoke about African-American
women and their contributions

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:42.280
to American society in
particular through food.

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:45.900
And I was astounded, I hadn't
heard anyone speak that way.

00:27:45.900 --> 00:27:49.490
And so, I ran over to the
groupie gaggle that was hanging

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:51.460
around him, I had
no idea who he was,

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:53.020
but obviously everyone else did.

00:27:53.020 --> 00:27:56.980
And I had shared that with
him that I had no idea,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:28:00.060
I'd never heard anyone
speak that way.

00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:03.560
And he said I've just returned
from the Library of Congress

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:06.210
and I have something in
my briefcase for you,

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:08.400
meet me in the press room.

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:11.560
And so, I waited for him in
the lobby of the press room

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:14.100
of the hotel and he went
through his briefcase

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:19.430
and he had this disheveled stack
of wrinkled pages from a book

00:28:19.430 --> 00:28:26.570
from 1912 called the Kentucky
Cookbook by a colored woman.

00:28:26.570 --> 00:28:30.920
He said he didn't know what
he was supposed to do with it,

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:35.010
but obviously it was intended
for me and so he gave me

00:28:35.010 --> 00:28:37.220
that copy of the book.

00:28:37.220 --> 00:28:44.230
I have to go by year to find it.

00:28:44.230 --> 00:28:49.140
So, I had this stack of papers

00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:53.010
and again I wasn't entirely sure
what I wanted to do with it.

00:28:53.010 --> 00:28:57.030
But gradually I started thinking
more and more about cookbooks

00:28:57.030 --> 00:28:59.690
as a mechanism for
telling a story.

00:28:59.690 --> 00:29:02.200
I still didn't realize
that they could be a tool

00:29:02.200 --> 00:29:06.280
that would change social
history and improve the status

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:08.910
and the perception of an
entire group of people.

00:29:08.910 --> 00:29:14.560
I really was still just in
pursuit of my own story.

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:21.080
So, another couple of
years go by and now Egerton

00:29:21.080 --> 00:29:23.700
and I are talking
about other content

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:28.020
and I encounter a book
called the Bluegrass Cookbook

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:32.810
and it was published in 1904 by
a white woman named Minnie Fox

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:37.920
and her brother John C. Fox
was a writer for the Atlantic.

00:29:37.920 --> 00:29:42.160
And they published this book and
again as John Egerton had done,

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:45.040
they gave credit to these
African-American women

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:47.090
and they did that with images.

00:29:47.090 --> 00:29:50.610
So not only did they attribute
recipes to these people in a way

00:29:50.610 --> 00:29:54.140
that was not a caricature
or a disparaging image

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:56.900
like that plantation era mammy

00:29:56.900 --> 00:30:01.030
that I was seeing
throughout history all

00:30:01.030 --> 00:30:05.140
of a sudden here was a group
of white people from Kentucky

00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:10.400
who had the same kind of passion
that Egerton and I both had

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:13.500
for these historic women.

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:17.270
And so, we approached the
University of Kentucky Press

00:30:17.270 --> 00:30:23.290
and they agreed to republish
that book and facsimile

00:30:23.290 --> 00:30:25.320
with a new introduction by me.

00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:29.530
And that brought me to my second
time and visit here at the --

00:30:29.530 --> 00:30:31.900
that brought me to my
visit here, my first visit

00:30:31.900 --> 00:30:35.580
to the Library of Congress
in the late 1990's.

00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:39.740
I came here and dug
into the archives

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:43.830
to explore African-American
writings to try to understand

00:30:43.830 --> 00:30:47.180
who in their right mind the
turn-of-the-century would've

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:51.090
written a book with a
title by a colored woman,

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:53.510
it didn't make much sense to me.

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:58.090
And so, I set out to understand
more about black cookbooks.

00:30:58.090 --> 00:31:01.050
And while I was here
I encountered several

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:04.060
of the rare books, rare
African-American books

00:31:04.060 --> 00:31:08.310
that are here in the collection
and then I was hooked,

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.960
like I mean like as
they say mainline,

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:12.430
I don't know should I say that.

00:31:12.430 --> 00:31:17.740
I started telling people my
passion and people who traveled

00:31:17.740 --> 00:31:19.910
around the country would
bring books back to me

00:31:19.910 --> 00:31:22.350
when they were on vacation.

00:31:22.350 --> 00:31:26.590
They would bring back little $2
pamphlets that they encountered

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:32.030
in secondhand stores and
books just started sort

00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:34.710
of coming to me.

00:31:34.710 --> 00:31:43.610
And I didn't really know how to
become a collector in earnest,

00:31:43.610 --> 00:31:48.910
but the internet
changed my life.

00:31:48.910 --> 00:31:55.660
The University of Alabama has
I think what is the largest

00:31:55.660 --> 00:31:58.070
collection of African-American
cookbooks,

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:00.640
the William Lupton collection.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:05.970
And this book, this collection
has some 450 books in it

00:32:05.970 --> 00:32:11.970
and that number is comprised of
duplicates, multiple editions,

00:32:11.970 --> 00:32:14.920
there are some in facsimile,
and there is a large number

00:32:14.920 --> 00:32:18.550
of books there that are
community cookbooks right,

00:32:18.550 --> 00:32:23.480
that I would never be able to
get in my local, in my area.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:25.560
And so, I used that
book as a shop,

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:30.100
that list as a shopping list
and I started entering titles

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:37.540
of books into the
browser at bookfinder.com

00:32:37.540 --> 00:32:41.200
and I just would wait
every now and then

00:32:41.200 --> 00:32:44.440
for something to pop up.

00:32:44.440 --> 00:32:48.550
One of the first books
that I was just determined

00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:57.660
to have was a book from 1936,
it was called Eliza's Cookbook.

00:33:03.120 --> 00:33:07.360
It's the yellow one, I was
desperate to have this book

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:09.820
because it was -- it's
called Eliza's Cookbook,

00:33:09.820 --> 00:33:12.220
Favorite Recipes Compiled

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:16.020
by the Negro Culinary
Art Club of Los Angeles.

00:33:16.020 --> 00:33:20.780
So, I'm from Los Angeles and
there I started to have an idea

00:33:20.780 --> 00:33:24.850
of who my grandmother
was in print on the page.

00:33:24.850 --> 00:33:27.160
She was a lovely woman
and she was talented

00:33:27.160 --> 00:33:28.860
and she was intelligent
and she wasn't

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:32.800
at all this disparaging thing
that I had seen so often

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:37.140
on the pages of history and
I had to have this book.

00:33:37.140 --> 00:33:39.710
Now keep in mind, I was a
stay-at-home mother taking my

00:33:39.710 --> 00:33:43.570
kids back and forth to swimming
and I was doing this in secret.

00:33:43.570 --> 00:33:46.790
My husband until I started this
tour had no idea how much I had

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:49.380
really been investing
in these books.

00:33:49.380 --> 00:33:52.900
And so, I entered the
title on an eBay auction,

00:33:52.900 --> 00:33:55.800
the book popped up for $1.

00:33:55.800 --> 00:34:00.680
And I was exhilarated, but I
didn't know anything about eBay,

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:03.570
so I went next-door to talk to
my neighbor who was a fanatic

00:34:03.570 --> 00:34:06.640
about eBay and she taught
me all of the secrets.

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:09.490
She taught me how to set
my clock to make sure

00:34:09.490 --> 00:34:11.820
that the tick-tock timing

00:34:11.820 --> 00:34:14.800
on my watch matched
their countdown clock.

00:34:14.800 --> 00:34:18.990
She told me not to enter the
title, not to enter my interest

00:34:18.990 --> 00:34:22.280
or my bid because then others
would know there was a value

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:25.390
to this book that
had shown up for $1.

00:34:25.390 --> 00:34:28.630
And so, I waited until
the two-minute warning

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:30.390
that she gave me and then

00:34:30.390 --> 00:34:32.850
and I had been watching
the number sort of tick up

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:36.450
and it was somewhere you know
in the couple hundred dollars.

00:34:36.450 --> 00:34:39.340
I thought I can live with that
I'll call my mom something

00:34:39.340 --> 00:34:40.640
like that.

00:34:40.640 --> 00:34:44.610
And so, I typed in my bid
and then I closed my eyes

00:34:44.610 --> 00:34:49.370
and pushed the button, you know
like he's going to kill me.

00:34:49.370 --> 00:34:55.170
So, I entered $400 and
then you wait and it seems

00:34:55.170 --> 00:34:56.860
like you're waiting forever.

00:34:56.860 --> 00:35:01.260
But the note, the little
blinking notice came back

00:35:01.260 --> 00:35:05.890
and said you've won
and I was so excited,

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:10.300
but I was also terrified
like I'm going to send $400

00:35:10.300 --> 00:35:13.630
to a stranger that I don't
know and I have no way to know

00:35:13.630 --> 00:35:15.950
if this book is authentic,
I don't know what condition,

00:35:15.950 --> 00:35:17.570
you know I don't know anything.

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:19.990
But I was determined
to have a book

00:35:19.990 --> 00:35:24.460
that put my grandmother
in this category.

00:35:24.460 --> 00:35:28.540
I called the woman in
San Diego and apparently,

00:35:28.540 --> 00:35:30.690
she had been cleaning out
her grandmother's attic

00:35:30.690 --> 00:35:32.460
and found this book,
had no idea the value

00:35:32.460 --> 00:35:34.960
and she was you know just
astounded at what she was

00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:37.160
about to earn for this book.

00:35:37.160 --> 00:35:40.810
And so, my life went
on like that for years.

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:43.150
I just kept entering
more and more titles

00:35:43.150 --> 00:35:46.160
and every time something popped
up, it didn't matter they were

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:47.940
at that point not
very expensive,

00:35:47.940 --> 00:35:51.380
so I was still paying very
small amounts for the books

00:35:51.380 --> 00:35:54.190
and really no amount
of money mattered I had

00:35:54.190 --> 00:35:55.560
to have these books.

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:59.250
And the longer that I collected
them the more that they started

00:35:59.250 --> 00:36:03.320
to organize themselves as
one of the essayists wrote

00:36:03.320 --> 00:36:08.210
into a social history that I was
able to tell a whole new story

00:36:08.210 --> 00:36:12.450
for the women who had cooked in
America's kitchens, who had been

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:15.890
so badly disparaged in
history and all of a sudden,

00:36:15.890 --> 00:36:19.390
I had the ability to break
what I started calling the

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:20.860
Jemima Code.

00:36:20.860 --> 00:36:26.290
So, I went to publishers, I had
a literary agent, I had 25 years

00:36:26.290 --> 00:36:29.220
in the food industry, so
I was pretty well known,

00:36:29.220 --> 00:36:32.130
nobody would buy this book.

00:36:32.130 --> 00:36:35.160
I proposed it as a
beautiful coffee table book

00:36:35.160 --> 00:36:39.150
that would have photographs
of all of the women inside.

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:43.970
I wanted everyone to fall in
love with them just in the way

00:36:43.970 --> 00:36:47.340
that I did and nobody cared.

00:36:47.340 --> 00:36:50.360
So, I found myself in
the same predicament

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:52.570
that my ancestors
had been in and many

00:36:52.570 --> 00:36:54.650
of these books were
self-published.

00:36:54.650 --> 00:36:58.960
Some of them are pamphlets,
some of them were even published

00:36:58.960 --> 00:37:03.550
by manufacturers who
were trying to get people

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:05.880
to buy more of their products.

00:37:05.880 --> 00:37:08.710
Some of them were books
published by universities

00:37:08.710 --> 00:37:14.310
on behalf of the cook who had
been feeding the athletic team.

00:37:18.070 --> 00:37:21.860
There was a food editor who
worked for Ebony Magazine

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:26.040
and she was asked by Carnation
to produce a recipe collection

00:37:26.040 --> 00:37:32.050
on their behalf using recipes,
Carnation recipes in the 1940's.

00:37:32.050 --> 00:37:35.350
And so, as I went along I just
kept collecting and trying

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:40.300
to convince a literary agent or
a publisher to buy this book.

00:37:40.300 --> 00:37:43.780
And in my frustration even
though I am a journalist I

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:49.000
decided to just take the
project to the internet,

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.910
the place where I had really --
that had saved the collection,

00:37:53.910 --> 00:37:55.890
I wanted to take the
books back there.

00:37:55.890 --> 00:38:01.100
And so, I started a blog
reluctantly and I was going

00:38:01.100 --> 00:38:04.600
to tell the story of every one
of these authors and so I wrote

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:06.410
that this would be
a one-year project

00:38:06.410 --> 00:38:07.940
and if people received
them the way

00:38:07.940 --> 00:38:10.450
that I did then I'd
keep going with it.

00:38:10.450 --> 00:38:13.640
And I really just abandoned the
idea of publishing this book.

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:20.100
And then the University of
Texas encountered the website

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:22.370
and they came to me and
said we want to publish

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:24.610
that book under one condition.

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:29.520
And I said sure what
and they said we want it

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:33.120
to be a beautiful
coffee table book.

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:37.300
I thought I was going to die.

00:38:37.300 --> 00:38:39.890
Really, this is what
they envisioned,

00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:42.130
they wanted a book about books.

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:46.370
They wanted, they understood
my passion and my desire

00:38:46.370 --> 00:38:48.630
to really change
the representation,

00:38:48.630 --> 00:38:51.360
to change the written history
of African-American women

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:53.070
who had worked in this country.

00:38:53.070 --> 00:38:55.530
And we knew that if we started

00:38:55.530 --> 00:38:58.540
with recipes people
wouldn't get it yet,

00:38:58.540 --> 00:39:02.220
people would think
all kinds of things.

00:39:02.220 --> 00:39:04.340
So, we knew that we
just had to validate

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:07.260
that the women even
existed first.

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:10.160
And there are books in this
collection that are co-authored

00:39:10.160 --> 00:39:14.060
by black-and-white women as
you can see here, this book is

00:39:14.060 --> 00:39:19.470
from the 80's, Viola's
Favorite Recipes.

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:24.310
There are books that have
incredible illustrations inside

00:39:24.310 --> 00:39:25.610
of them.

00:39:25.610 --> 00:39:28.760
If you can see Ma Chance's book
on Caribbean French cooking.

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:30.900
There are others like her

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:35.670
who give us very detailed
illustration of how

00:39:35.670 --> 00:39:41.310
to chop a certain dish
or how this guy in 1970,

00:39:41.310 --> 00:39:47.320
1972 this is a diet book
published for African-American,

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:54.750
for people in general and he
gives four weeks' worth of menus

00:39:54.750 --> 00:39:57.200
and does things that
we think about already,

00:39:57.200 --> 00:40:00.740
like telling you how much
is a serving size of pasta

00:40:00.740 --> 00:40:02.140
for example on this page.

00:40:02.140 --> 00:40:04.250
And so, what this book started

00:40:04.250 --> 00:40:06.660
to do was really
reveal an intelligence

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:08.550
that hadn't ever been associated

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:09.990
with African-American
cooks before.

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:14.040
We had previously been either
acknowledged as great cooks

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:16.980
because we came by that
knowledge naturally

00:40:16.980 --> 00:40:20.470
with some kind of
a natural instinct.

00:40:20.470 --> 00:40:23.450
Some authors in the 20's
even described as having sort

00:40:23.450 --> 00:40:28.660
of a voodoo magic that we
cooked with, it's very insulting

00:40:28.660 --> 00:40:30.940
and complimentary at
the same time right.

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:33.530
Again, that's the messaging
of a code that it speaks

00:40:33.530 --> 00:40:35.740
to us all very differently.

00:40:35.740 --> 00:40:40.300
And so, it became evident that
there was an intelligence here

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:42.010
and there was also a social arc.

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:46.940
So, I've been able to divide
my content now by generations

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:51.740
of women and I've been able
to extract characteristics

00:40:51.740 --> 00:40:54.840
and values that have not
been identified before.

00:40:54.840 --> 00:41:00.060
For example, in 1827 the
oldest book in the collection,

00:41:00.060 --> 00:41:03.120
I won't go through them all,
but I do like to just wrap

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:06.240
up with the 19th
century authors.

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:14.320
In 1827, Robert Roberts wrote
The House Servant's Directory.

00:41:14.320 --> 00:41:18.360
He was the butler in
the governor's mansion

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:23.580
in Massachusetts
and he writes a book

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:26.110
that is essentially
a training manual

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.190
for future generations
of workers.

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:33.540
History would have portrayed
this book as just another way

00:41:33.540 --> 00:41:35.330
to create more servants.

00:41:35.330 --> 00:41:37.360
It would have continued
to disparage the idea

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:40.160
that African-Americans
had any knowledge,

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:41.870
but this is a love letter.

00:41:41.870 --> 00:41:47.070
The way that he has written to
his charges about their work is

00:41:47.070 --> 00:41:50.270
so profoundly intimate
and smart.

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:55.170
He speaks to them about
punctuality and proper dress

00:41:55.170 --> 00:41:56.670
and decorum on the job.

00:41:56.670 --> 00:42:01.530
He even talks to them about
keeping your feet clean,

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:03.660
which I thought was
really interesting.

00:42:03.660 --> 00:42:06.660
I have a really great story
about collecting right.

00:42:06.660 --> 00:42:11.420
So, this book, this was a book
about women as the title implies

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:14.400
because there is a history
associated with men,

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:19.690
Thomas Jefferson had a black
chef that he had trained

00:42:19.690 --> 00:42:23.930
in France as did George
Washington, so there are stories

00:42:23.930 --> 00:42:27.210
about black men, but there are
no stories about black women.

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:31.910
And so, I wasn't really
looking for Robert Roberts,

00:42:31.910 --> 00:42:35.300
but I was in New York City
and I called a book dealer

00:42:35.300 --> 00:42:38.580
and I said hey, I'm here do
you have anything you know

00:42:38.580 --> 00:42:41.920
that maybe I don't have and she
said everybody knows you have

00:42:41.920 --> 00:42:43.480
everything already.

00:42:43.480 --> 00:42:46.920
And I said well there's a couple
of first editions I'm looking

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:51.160
for and so she said
well okay what

00:42:51.160 --> 00:42:54.350
and so I told her
I wanted this one

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:59.020
and she said call me
back in 10 minutes.

00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:00.360
So, I called her
back in 10 minutes

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:02.630
and she said can
you come over here

00:43:02.630 --> 00:43:06.060
in the village they're
bringing you the book.

00:43:07.260 --> 00:43:09.900
Like what do you mean
they're bringing me the book

00:43:09.900 --> 00:43:11.200
and so she said just come

00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:12.730
over here they're
bringing you the book.

00:43:12.730 --> 00:43:17.220
So, a disheveled guy who
was like obviously working

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:20.390
in this man's home
came in the store

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:25.670
with a crumpled grocery bag
in his hand and he handed it

00:43:25.670 --> 00:43:30.460
to Bonnie and Bonnie handed
it to me and we opened it

00:43:30.460 --> 00:43:34.730
and this book in first
edition from 1827 was inside

00:43:34.730 --> 00:43:38.330
of that bag and I collapsed.

00:43:38.330 --> 00:43:44.600
I had an immediate connection
to these people in a way

00:43:44.600 --> 00:43:45.900
that I haven't been
able to explain

00:43:45.900 --> 00:43:47.740
to any other audience right.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:49.430
Everyone else just
thinks oh yeah,

00:43:49.430 --> 00:43:51.150
you did a great job,
you changed history.

00:43:51.150 --> 00:43:53.790
You know there's something
very unique and special

00:43:53.790 --> 00:43:57.100
about the intimate relationship
between a collector who is

00:43:57.100 --> 00:44:01.900
in pursuit of their passion
for whatever that reason,

00:44:01.900 --> 00:44:04.200
whether it's a social history
that you want to change

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:07.470
or whether it's just for your
own incredible knowledge.

00:44:07.470 --> 00:44:13.130
So, I will tell you about
two more, maybe three,

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:16.230
I have four minutes, I can
do it in three minutes.

00:44:16.230 --> 00:44:20.140
So, this one, this is my
first holding of this one

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:24.070
and I'm shivering up here if
you can't see it and I have been

00:44:24.070 --> 00:44:28.370
for the last hour since
Mark gave it to me.

00:44:28.370 --> 00:44:33.210
This lovely little book is
from 1848 and was published

00:44:33.210 --> 00:44:38.280
by this man Tunis Campbell
and among his accolades,

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:43.140
he's responsible for the drill
that you have experienced

00:44:43.140 --> 00:44:45.480
at hotels and banquet service

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:50.260
when the waitstaff is all
located kind of around the room

00:44:50.260 --> 00:44:52.420
and then they wait until
the exact right moment

00:44:52.420 --> 00:44:56.720
and they march out and they
remove the cover of the dish.

00:44:56.720 --> 00:45:01.340
He's part of why we do that, it
was actually a military drill

00:45:01.340 --> 00:45:03.540
that he incorporated
in his hotel service.

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:06.110
And so, I use little
stories like that to try

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:09.800
to encourage the next generation
of young people that there are

00:45:09.800 --> 00:45:13.040
so many incredible
opportunities in the food world

00:45:13.040 --> 00:45:15.960
that don't have to do with
food service or cooking

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:19.850
or being a chef, that
there is lots of other ways

00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:22.010
that we can uplift young people

00:45:22.010 --> 00:45:27.390
from poverty using
the food industry.

00:45:27.390 --> 00:45:31.150
This is a really wonderful
book, the only copy of this book

00:45:31.150 --> 00:45:34.370
that we know of is
in the archives

00:45:34.370 --> 00:45:36.150
at the University of Michigan.

00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:39.680
This is the first
known cookbook,

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:43.480
the other two were
hotel manager books,

00:45:43.480 --> 00:45:47.920
but this is the first
recipe collection from 1866.

00:45:47.920 --> 00:45:49.820
And what is compelling
about this book

00:45:49.820 --> 00:45:54.720
and what I tell young people
is that this was a free woman

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:58.840
of color who had to, she
had a handicapped child,

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:03.040
she had been robbed twice
and she was using food

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:05.630
as a tool for her own uplift.

00:46:05.630 --> 00:46:14.000
She started a catering company,
she had a boarding house.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.480
And so, what I like to
tell people about her

00:46:17.480 --> 00:46:23.250
and about the next women Abby
Fisher is that they were women

00:46:23.250 --> 00:46:26.350
who were entrepreneurs
and we don't tend to think

00:46:26.350 --> 00:46:29.180
of African-American women in
the kitchen as entrepreneurs,

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:31.530
but these are women
who used food

00:46:31.530 --> 00:46:36.020
to achieve economic
independence right.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:41.050
Abby Fisher was a woman who had
been enslaved in North Carolina

00:46:41.050 --> 00:46:44.920
and she and her husband
relocated to San Francisco

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:47.530
where she operated,
they operated a pickles

00:46:47.530 --> 00:46:49.610
and preserves company.

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:54.210
And that she won multiple
awards for her pickles

00:46:54.210 --> 00:46:57.090
and so the white women in her
community, both of these women,

00:46:57.090 --> 00:46:58.680
they rallied around these women

00:46:58.680 --> 00:47:02.530
and they helped them get
their books published.

00:47:02.530 --> 00:47:06.420
The first time I
actually saw this book was

00:47:06.420 --> 00:47:11.480
at the Schlesinger Library and
I guess that's as good a place

00:47:11.480 --> 00:47:14.270
as any to wrap up to say

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:22.650
that along the way I was using
my reporter skills to aggregate,

00:47:22.650 --> 00:47:26.440
to understand, to
represent these people,

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:30.370
but I didn't quite
know about collecting.

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:36.190
And I attended a seminar at
Radcliffe that taught me how

00:47:36.190 --> 00:47:43.220
to read a cookbook without the
bias of race or gender and how

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:48.130
to look at the nuances of print
and paper and ink and choice

00:47:48.130 --> 00:47:51.000
of color, and those
cute little squiggles

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:54.160
that I'm certain you guys know
exactly what the name of it is

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:56.500
that are on every page.

00:47:56.500 --> 00:48:02.700
And I learned a lot about
collecting from that session.

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:06.400
So, I'll leave you
with where we started.

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:09.280
Lena Richard remember
her, the book that I took

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:11.490
out of the collection?

00:48:11.490 --> 00:48:17.150
It turns out, I guess I should
memorize the page these books

00:48:17.150 --> 00:48:19.820
are on, it turns out that

00:48:19.820 --> 00:48:22.600
that little paperback
had been reproduced three

00:48:22.600 --> 00:48:25.550
or four different times by Lena.

00:48:25.550 --> 00:48:31.490
And the first time was 1939
and she published the book

00:48:31.490 --> 00:48:33.540
by herself, it was a
self-published book,

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:36.980
she was an entrepreneur and
a restaurateur in New Orleans

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:41.850
and she had her own television
show before Julia Child did

00:48:41.850 --> 00:48:43.740
in 1941.

00:48:43.740 --> 00:48:51.760
So, Miss Lena published her
book in 1939 and James Beard,

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:55.830
the great father of American
cooking learned of her book

00:48:55.830 --> 00:48:59.330
and he approached his
publisher and asked them

00:48:59.330 --> 00:49:04.690
to reissue the book for
her, which they did in 1940.

00:49:04.690 --> 00:49:07.060
And so, the book -- oh, that's
right it's not in 80's it's

00:49:07.060 --> 00:49:12.540
in 30's, they did that for her,
only they changed the title.

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:19.030
So, the top book is the blue
book Lena Richard's book,

00:49:19.030 --> 00:49:23.330
she calls it Lena Richard's
New Orleans Cookbook.

00:49:23.330 --> 00:49:28.080
One year later the book
appears as New Orleans Cookbook

00:49:28.080 --> 00:49:32.200
by Lena Richard and this
beautiful self-portrait

00:49:32.200 --> 00:49:36.480
