Eugene is not somebody that
I even knew about growing

01:01:13.400 --> 01:01:16.760
up next-door to Mobile, Alabama
in Pascagoula, Mississippi,

01:01:16.760 --> 01:01:18.870
I lived my whole life there
and I never heard about him.

01:01:18.870 --> 01:01:23.020
But as I read his Untidy Pilgrim
it's kind of autobiographical

01:01:23.020 --> 01:01:26.880
in some ways and collecting his
books, going through his poetry

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:29.560
and discovering more about
him and reading about people

01:01:29.560 --> 01:01:33.310
who knew him and his life
there's many layers to it.

01:01:33.310 --> 01:01:35.100
And one thing that's constant
through all of them is he liked

01:01:35.100 --> 01:01:37.500
to have a good time and have
a party wherever he was.

01:01:37.500 --> 01:01:39.470
And so, that's how he was
mainly known by people

01:01:39.470 --> 01:01:41.610
like Andy Warhol lived
down the hall from him

01:01:41.610 --> 01:01:44.070
and he called him Baby
Andrew wand they staged

01:01:44.070 --> 01:01:46.240
like the first happening
at NOMA.

01:01:46.240 --> 01:01:48.550
And one of the things
I discovered

01:01:48.550 --> 01:01:50.730
about him along the way
is that sometimes he liked

01:01:50.730 --> 01:01:55.020
to include jokes and little
hidden messages throughout his

01:01:55.020 --> 01:01:57.610
work so he wrote under a
pseudonym called Sebastian

01:01:57.610 --> 01:02:00.040
Willoughby and so that
was a challenge in itself

01:02:00.040 --> 01:02:02.790
because no one really had gone
through and done a collection

01:02:02.790 --> 01:02:04.630
or looked and tried
to find every work

01:02:04.630 --> 01:02:06.040
where that was included.

01:02:06.040 --> 01:02:08.170
And so, I went and I
tried to find every book

01:02:08.170 --> 01:02:10.400
that was illustrated by some
random person named Sebastian

01:02:10.400 --> 01:02:11.970
Willoughby and I would buy
the book and it would come

01:02:11.970 --> 01:02:14.020
in the mail and it would
be him or it wouldn't be.

01:02:14.020 --> 01:02:16.700
And so, I came across
some really great finds

01:02:16.700 --> 01:02:18.630
of his along the way.

01:02:18.630 --> 01:02:19.930
And it's still growing,

01:02:19.930 --> 01:02:21.230
I'm still discovering
different things,

01:02:21.230 --> 01:02:22.820
but I thoroughly enjoyed it

01:02:22.820 --> 01:02:24.670
and I really wish I could
have met him in person.

01:02:24.670 --> 01:02:26.170
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: He
seems like a great mystery

01:02:26.170 --> 01:02:27.520
and a great deal of fun

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:30.590
and I love the Andy Warhol
story I have to confess.

01:02:30.590 --> 01:02:33.200
What do you think is the
most unusual object you have

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:37.780
in this collection or perhaps
one that was hardest to come by?

01:02:37.780 --> 01:02:41.040
&gt;&gt; Luke Kelly: So, the hardest
to come by I didn't quite know

01:02:41.040 --> 01:02:42.520
that I was going to come by it.

01:02:42.520 --> 01:02:45.710
Like I said about the Sebastian
Willoughby there was this book

01:02:45.710 --> 01:02:49.150
of these German, it's really
arcane and I don't have --

01:02:49.150 --> 01:02:51.050
I confess I don't have a
clue as to how the history

01:02:51.050 --> 01:02:52.350
of these poems came to be.

01:02:52.350 --> 01:02:54.270
But there's this
translation of them

01:02:54.270 --> 01:02:57.870
and Eugene did the
illustrations for them

01:02:57.870 --> 01:02:59.190
under the name Sebastian
Willoughby.

01:02:59.190 --> 01:03:02.320
So, I ordered the book online,
it came in and next to one

01:03:02.320 --> 01:03:03.720
of the characters
on the cover of it

01:03:03.720 --> 01:03:06.190
to his foot is a little
EW, it's like I have it

01:03:06.190 --> 01:03:10.680
and then I opened it up and
it's signed from Eugene Walter,

01:03:10.680 --> 01:03:12.850
but he doesn't sign it
Eugene Walter he signs it

01:03:12.850 --> 01:03:14.170
Sebastian Willoughby.

01:03:14.170 --> 01:03:18.090
And it's to his roommate when
he lived in Rome, he lived right

01:03:18.090 --> 01:03:20.240
above Cleopatra where her
kitchen would have been

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:23.010
and his name was William Weaver

01:03:23.010 --> 01:03:27.520
and he translated Thomas
Wolfe's poetry into prose,

01:03:27.520 --> 01:03:32.890
no he did excuse me, the
Rose, I'm blanking the title.

01:03:32.890 --> 01:03:34.190
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation:
The Tennessee Williams,

01:03:34.190 --> 01:03:36.030
The Rose of Tennessee.

01:03:36.030 --> 01:03:37.330
&gt;&gt; Luke Kelly: [Inaudible]
Echoes.

01:03:37.330 --> 01:03:38.630
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: Echoes
[inaudible] the Rose.

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:39.930
&gt;&gt; Luke Kelly: And so, it was
just a great, I didn't buy it

01:03:39.930 --> 01:03:43.260
because of the inscription,
I actually had no idea

01:03:43.260 --> 01:03:45.660
that it was there,
but when it came

01:03:45.660 --> 01:03:47.750
in it was just a
terrific discovering

01:03:47.750 --> 01:03:49.910
and it's probably my favorite
item in the collection I think.

01:03:49.910 --> 01:03:51.920
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: And so,
we'll close just if you could

01:03:51.920 --> 01:03:54.170
to the audience because
I really do have

01:03:54.170 --> 01:03:56.310
to confess it was a
cold read at the title

01:03:56.310 --> 01:04:02.820
and I thought oh we're going to
be reading about some chronicler

01:04:02.820 --> 01:04:06.760
of apes and chimpanzees
and I'm sure it's a very

01:04:06.760 --> 01:04:08.060
good collection.

01:04:08.060 --> 01:04:10.470
Could you tell us what the king
of the monkeys actually means?

01:04:10.470 --> 01:04:13.070
&gt;&gt; Luke Kelly: So, Eugene his
favorite animal was the monkey.

01:04:13.070 --> 01:04:15.780
When he went to the
natural history museum

01:04:15.780 --> 01:04:19.740
in York he encountered
this monkey that looked

01:04:19.740 --> 01:04:21.120
like he was wearing a tuxedo

01:04:21.120 --> 01:04:22.710
and he just thought it
was the funniest thing.

01:04:22.710 --> 01:04:24.880
And so, he would go
all the way and say --

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:26.480
all the time and when
he was in Paris and say,

01:04:26.480 --> 01:04:28.460
oh darling you're the
queen of the monkeys.

01:04:28.460 --> 01:04:30.150
And so, he was kind
of their king and kind

01:04:30.150 --> 01:04:32.970
of just shepherded them
around and enjoyed life.

01:04:32.970 --> 01:04:36.890
And so, it kind of embodies
his philosophy of life.

01:04:36.890 --> 01:04:39.920
Monkeys do what they want,
they're very kind of boastful

01:04:39.920 --> 01:04:42.090
and arrogant, but like
to have a good time

01:04:42.090 --> 01:04:45.710
and that's the way he thought,
he was larger-than-life

01:04:45.710 --> 01:04:48.520
in many ways and it
was just a joy to be

01:04:48.520 --> 01:04:50.360
around for everyone
that knew him.

01:04:50.360 --> 01:04:51.660
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: Right.

